        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer305092880" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5405030622863340518">This one of those books, that make you think deeply about the greatness of nature and how small mankind is. I&apos;ll make this book one of my all time favorites, because when I finished it, I wanted to start reading it again. There&apos;s so much in it to think about and so much that I missed reading this first time. <br/>I have a crush on countries with mountains, and especially those with snowcovered caps. Whenever I&apos;m is Switzerland, or Norway I&apos;m enjoying the great glaciers: those mighty rivers of ice. <br/>I </span>
  <span id="freeText5405030622863340518" style="display:none">This one of those books, that make you think deeply about the greatness of nature and how small mankind is. I'll make this book one of my all time favorites, because when I finished it, I wanted to start reading it again. There's so much in it to think about and so much that I missed reading this first time. <br />I have a crush on countries with mountains, and especially those with snowcovered caps. Whenever I'm is Switzerland, or Norway I'm enjoying the great glaciers: those mighty rivers of ice. <br />I don't think I will see the Himalayas other than in National Geographic documentaries. I have been on top of the Alps in Switzerland and have seen the longest glacier (the Aletsch) from both ends (near Moosfluh and at the Jungfraujoch); I was at the Gornergrat near Zermatt and every time I was awestrucken because the view was so splendid. <br />Reading Peter Matthiessen's book I felt the same awe and the wonder for the majesty of those enormous blocks of rock. <br />Long after we will be gone, those mountains will still stand.</span>
