<div id="review_1587165471" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1587165471" />
    <a title="Tom Reeves" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5889912-tom-reeves"><img alt="Tom Reeves" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1433099509p2/5889912.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1587165471?book_show_action=true">Dec 20, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tom Reeves" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tom Reeves" href="/user/show/5889912-tom-reeves">Tom Reeves</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1587165471" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10503244619243248267">I was going to give 4 stars at first, but I think its 5 in the end. The book has lingered with me these days since I finished, I can&apos;t help but think it is important. Its a lesson, a lesson into the essence of being. It brings Western and Eastern thought together in a meditative journey through the mountains. It feels fresh, genuine and alive. Matthiesen goes in search of the Snow Leopard but to me it seems that Tukten is the real focal point, the real mystical creature of his pilgrimage. My min</span>
  <span id="freeText10503244619243248267" style="display:none">I was going to give 4 stars at first, but I think its 5 in the end. The book has lingered with me these days since I finished, I can't help but think it is important. Its a lesson, a lesson into the essence of being. It brings Western and Eastern thought together in a meditative journey through the mountains. It feels fresh, genuine and alive. Matthiesen goes in search of the Snow Leopard but to me it seems that Tukten is the real focal point, the real mystical creature of his pilgrimage. My mind has certainly been altered by this book.</span>
